{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is the handoff between file discovery and execution order, not just a pure sort helper. A Unit test on a sorter can miss bugs where discovered filenames are filtered/parsing-mapped incorrectly before execution. Integration with a temp `migrations/` directory and a DB adapter/test DB that records execution sequence catches this. Rejected System: behavior does not require real subprocess/OS-network effects; no claim about cross-process timing or OS-specific file events.","test_description":"Create several `.sql` files with out-of-order numeric prefixes in a temp `migrations/` directory, run the runner once, and assert execution/order in `_migrations` is strictly ascending by numeric prefix.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at module interaction: runner reads `_migrations` state and decides whether to execute SQL. A Unit test of only the skip predicate can miss persistence/state-wiring bugs across runs. Integration with the same DB across two invocations is the minimum to expose real idempotency failures. Rejected System: behavior text only requires a subsequent run, not separate OS processes or real network conditions.","test_description":"Run migrations once, capture side effect (e.g., row insert or schema change count), run runner again against same DB, and assert no migration SQL re-executes and `_migrations` entries are unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug is at transaction + migration-loop interaction: DB rollback semantics plus runner stop-on-failure behavior. A pure Unit test cannot prove rollback of real SQL effects. Integration with a real local PostgreSQL test DB is needed to observe actual rollback and that later migration files are not applied. Rejected System: no subprocess orchestration requirement in behavior text; single runner invocation against local DB is sufficient.","test_description":"Prepare migration N with one successful statement then a failing statement, and migration N+1 with visible side effect. Run runner and assert: (1) effects from migration N are absent (rolled back), (2) N+1 did not run, (3) failure is reported.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires concurrent starts from separate processes. Real failure depends on inter-process race/locking timing with a real DB; mocked or single-process integration can pass while missing duplicate-apply races. Rejected Integration: disqualified by behavior text 'two instances ... at the same time' and 'across both instances', which requires subprocess-level concurrency.","test_description":"Launch two runner processes simultaneously against the same PostgreSQL instance with identical migration set; assert each migration appears once in `_migrations` and side effects indicate exactly-once application (no duplicates, no missed migrations).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is ordering/state bootstrap across modules (metadata-table initialization then migration execution). Unit tests of helper functions can miss sequencing bugs in the runner flow. Integration with fresh DB and at least one migration file is sufficient. Rejected System: no subprocess/OS/network-specific behavior is required beyond normal local DB interaction.","test_description":"Start with a fresh DB and one migration that assumes `_migrations` tracking exists; run runner and assert `_migrations` is created first and migration then applies successfully with a corresponding metadata row.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
